47:47.932 --> 47:50.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
models that you looked to,
right, leaders, writers,
musicians.

47:50.601 --> 47:53.003 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: Yes.

47:53.003 --> 47:56.941 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You also refer to
a kind of traditional black
narrative.

47:56.941 --> 48:02.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You said, the traditional black
narrative, I experienced racism,
I overcame racism.

48:02.780 --> 48:04.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you're specifically doing
something different or feeling
something different.

48:04.715 --> 48:06.117 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: Yes.

48:06.117 --> 48:08.352 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I don't think that it's
something to overcome.

48:08.352 --> 48:13.524 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that these are systems
that we are experiencing and
need to be dismantled, but

48:13.524 --> 48:20.030 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that there is a feeling,
particularly in black
communities, that one does the
hard

48:20.030 --> 48:25.336 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
work and does -- and presents
himself as twice as good and as
respectable, and that you will

48:25.336 --> 48:31.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be spared the sting of racism,
because it cannot touch you if
you present yourself as

48:31.709 --> 48:33.244 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
impenetrable to it.

48:33.244 --> 48:35.112 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And it's just not true.

48:35.112 --> 48:37.214 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BARACK OBAMA, President of the
United States: Mr. Speaker...

48:37.214 --> 48:40.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: We have
lived through eight years of a
black presidency, and we

48:40.918 --> 48:45.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have seen the amount of racist
attacks against him, a man who,
by all measures, is the most

48:45.890 --> 48:51.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
respectable black man that the
United States has ever produced,
and achieved the highest

48:51.395 --> 48:56.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
office in the land and can still
be hit with racism and has faced
the most recalcitrant

48:56.433 --> 49:00.271 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Republican Congress in history,
on the basis of racist backlash.

49:00.271 --> 49:04.208 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, that idea just does not sit.

49:04.208 --> 49:08.612 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Barack Obama,
this presidency that we have
lived through, is perhaps the

49:08.612 --> 49:11.949 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
most pivotal figure in this book
for your life and for our times.

49:11.949 --> 49:14.218 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: Yes.

49:14.218 --> 49:17.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But, for you,
most interestingly, what comes
through is the deep ambivalence

49:17.822 --> 49:22.960 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you feel about him, right, that
he is almost not who you wanted
to be.

49:22.960 --> 49:25.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: Yes, well,
he's not -- it's not a question
of whether I want him to be

49:25.529 --> 49:26.564 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
anyone.

49:26.564 --> 49:29.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

49:29.066 --> 49:33.537 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that he is who he is,
and he's a product of certain
traditions and ideology.

49:33.537 --> 49:38.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he's only -- he's only
president -- the first black
president possible because of

49:38.642 --> 49:43.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the ideology that he espouses,
because he is sort of -- he is a
very centrist, mainstream

49:43.614 --> 49:49.420 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Democrat whose politics are not
going to challenge the status
quo in radical ways.

49:49.420 --> 49:54.325 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, yes, he's successful
in large part because of that.

49:54.325 --> 49:59.630 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he's the first black
president in part because his
narrative, his story doesn't
remind

49:59.630 --> 50:03.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people of America's racism, in
the same ways that a person who
is a descendent of slavery

50:03.133 --> 50:04.702 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
would.

50:04.702 --> 50:08.405 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He is not of that.

50:08.405 --> 50:13.677 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, there are certain things
that make Barack Obama possible
and make him an inspirational

50:13.677 --> 50:17.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
figure in a lot of ways, but
then there is the way in which
he talks to and about black

50:17.848 --> 50:20.551 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
America.

50:20.551 --> 50:27.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that a lot of what he --
the work that he has done in
assuring voters who turned

50:27.324 --> 50:31.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out, white voters to turn out
for him, was that he wasn't
going to play favoritism to

50:31.929 --> 50:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
black America, that he wasn't a
race man, that he wasn't
concerned about the idea of

50:36.500 --> 50:41.672 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
racism to the point of policy
changes and an actual shift in
the way in which we conduct

50:41.672 --> 50:44.174 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
business here in
the United States.

50:44.174 --> 50:48.979 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And you wanted
something more from him and from
yourself, from others?

50:48.979 --> 50:54.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: I would
like to see more movement on the
ground and
consciousness-shifting

50:54.084 --> 51:00.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and discuss -- and discourse in
our everyday lives, so that we
produce the kind of politicians

51:00.024 --> 51:03.160 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that respond to that.

51:03.160 --> 51:08.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would like to see more of us
engaged in reckoning with the
history of the United States.

51:08.332 --> 51:13.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would like to see more of us
dealing with what the present of
racism looks like, so

51:13.437 --> 51:18.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we understand how this
country is built and who it's
meant to benefit.

51:18.042 --> 51:25.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in that way, when we, as
voting constituencies, shift the
way that we're thinking about
it,

51:25.983 --> 51:28.152 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
our politicians have no other
choice but to respond.

51:28.152 --> 51:30.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And what about
for yourself, finally?

51:30.788 --> 51:34.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You write near the end of the
book about wanting to become, as
you say, an honest black man

51:34.024 --> 51:35.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and a good black writer.

51:35.726 --> 51:37.328 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What does that mean?

51:37.328 --> 51:39.830 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What are you aspiring to?

51:39.830 --> 51:46.603 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MYCHAL DENZEL SMITH: The honesty
is that -- is knowing that there
has been a very masculinist

51:46.603 --> 51:51.608 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
narrative around black life in
the United States, and that
someone in my position, as

51:51.608 --> 51:58.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a cisgender, heterosexual black
man, knows what that experience
is and can continue to

51:58.782 --> 52:02.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
repeat it over and over again,
and never have to interrogate
complicity within other
structures

52:02.353 --> 52:05.055 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of oppressions.

52:05.055 --> 52:11.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think being honest means
that we start doing the work of
that interrogation for
ourselves,

52:11.462 --> 52:15.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and that gets us to a politics
that's more open and more
inclusive and talking about

52:15.366 --> 52:18.469 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
equality and just
for all people.

52:18.469 --> 52:20.971 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The book is
"Invisible Man, Got the Whole
World Watching: A Young Black

52:20.971 --> 52:22.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Man's Education."

